📚 UNIT 1 : Introduction to DBMS
What is Data?

Data = Raw Facts

Example:

Lucky
22
Delhi

These are just facts.

What is Information?

Processed Data = Information

Example:

Name = Lucky
Age = 22
City = Delhi

Now it has meaning.

What is Database?

A collection of related data stored together.

Example:

Student Database

Roll	Name	Age
101	Lucky	22
102	Rahul	21

This table is a database.

What is DBMS?

DBMS = Database Management System

Software used to create, store, update and manage databases.

Examples:

MySQL
Oracle Database
PostgreSQL
Microsoft SQL Server
Why DBMS?

Without DBMS:

Data stored in files

Problems:

❌ Data redundancy

❌ Data inconsistency

❌ Difficult searching

❌ Security issues

❌ No backup

With DBMS:

✅ Easy access

✅ Security

✅ Backup

✅ Data sharing

✅ Integrity

First Understand What a File System Is

Before DBMS, organizations used files to store data.

Example:

A college stores data in separate files:

Student.txt
101 Rahul CSE
102 Priya ECE
Marks.txt
101 DBMS 85
102 OS 90
Fee.txt
101 Paid
102 Pending

All data is stored in separate files.

This is called a File System.

What Problems Occur in File Systems?

Imagine a college with:

50,000 students
100 teachers
500 courses

Managing everything through files becomes difficult.

DBMS was created to solve these problems.

1. Data Redundancy (Duplication)
What is Redundancy?

Same data stored multiple times.

File System Example

Student file:

ID	Name	Branch
101	Rahul	CSE

Library file:

ID	Name	Branch
101	Rahul	CSE

Hostel file:

ID	Name	Branch
101	Rahul	CSE

Notice:

Rahul's information appears in multiple files.

This is redundancy.

Problems Caused

Suppose Rahul changes branch:

CSE → IT

Now you must update:

Student file
Library file
Hostel file

If one file remains unchanged:

Student File:

Rahul IT

Hostel File:

Rahul CSE

Now data becomes inconsistent.

How DBMS Solves It

Store student details once.

Student Table
ID	Name	Branch
101	Rahul	IT

Other tables reference Student_ID.

No repeated storage.

Less redundancy.

Interview Definition

Data redundancy means unnecessary duplication of data. DBMS minimizes redundancy by storing data in a centralized and structured manner.

2. Data Inconsistency
What is Inconsistency?

When same data has different values at different places.

File System Example

Student File:

Rahul IT

Library File:

Rahul CSE

Which one is correct?

Nobody knows.

This is inconsistency.

DBMS Solution

Only one source of truth.

Student table updated once.

Every department sees the same value.

Interview Definition

Data inconsistency occurs when multiple copies of the same data contain different values. DBMS reduces inconsistency by maintaining a single integrated database.

3. Difficult Data Access

Suppose Principal asks:

Show all CSE students whose marks are above 80.

File System

Need to:

Open Student file
Open Marks file
Compare records manually
Write program

Time-consuming.

DBMS

Simple SQL:

SELECT Name
FROM Student
WHERE Marks > 80;

Result in seconds.

Why Better?

Fast retrieval.

Easy querying.

No manual searching.

4. Poor Security
File System

Anyone with file access can open:

salary.txt
marks.txt
fees.txt

Very risky.

DBMS

Can assign permissions.

Example:

Teacher:

Can view marks
Cannot view salary

Account Department:

Can view fees
Cannot view marks

Student:

Can view own record only
Interview Definition

DBMS provides authorization and access control mechanisms to protect sensitive data.

5. No Concurrency Control
Example

Bank Account Balance:

10000

Two people access simultaneously.

User A

Withdraws 1000

Balance:

9000
User B

Withdraws 2000

Balance:

8000

Correct balance should be:

7000

But due to simultaneous access, one update may overwrite another.

DBMS Solution

Uses concurrency control and locking.

Final balance remains correct.

6. No Backup and Recovery

Suppose power failure occurs.

File System

Data may be lost permanently.

No recovery mechanism.

DBMS

Provides:

Backup
Recovery
Logs
Checkpoints

Can restore data.

Example

Bank server crashes.

DBMS restores transactions from logs.

Money remains safe.

7. Integrity Problems

Suppose Marks file contains:

Student_ID = 9999

But student 9999 doesn't exist.

File system won't stop it.

DBMS

Uses constraints.

Foreign Key
Student_ID

must exist in Student table.

Invalid records rejected.

8. No Data Sharing
File System

Departments maintain separate files.

Library file
Hostel file
Accounts file

Sharing becomes difficult.

DBMS

All departments use same database.

Easy sharing.

9. High Maintenance Cost

In file system:

Every new requirement needs:

New file
New program
New maintenance

Lots of effort.

DBMS

Just write queries.

Very flexible.

