The Real Secret: DBMS Uses a Structured Model

Instead of random files:

students.txt
marks.txt
fees.txt

DBMS creates a structured system:

Student Table
Teacher Table
Course Table
Marks Table
Attendance Table
Fee Table

And connects them through keys:

Student
   |
   | Student_ID
   |
Marks

Student
   |
   | Student_ID
   |
Attendance

Student
   |
   | Student_ID
   |
Fees

This structure allows DBMS to handle millions of records efficiently.

Interview Answer

Q: A college has 50,000 students. How does DBMS help compared to a file system?

Answer:

DBMS stores data in structured tables and maintains relationships using keys. It reduces redundancy, ensures consistency, 
supports fast searching through indexing, allows multiple users to access data simultaneously, provides security, enforces data integrity, 
and offers backup and recovery features. These capabilities make managing large amounts of college data much easier than using separate files.

